  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Afterword to Emperor Yejong's Collection of Poetic Exchanges
  author: Lee Kyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When the realm has not yet attained great peace, even a sovereign who loves the literary arts cannot sit with scholars and court poets to compose verses on wind and moon, nor taste the leisure of carefree pleasure. And when great peace prevails with ample time, should the ruler not favor literature—though a poet possessed talents equal to Shen Quan-qi, Song Zhi-wen, Yan Guo-gong, or Su Ting—how could he join the elegant gatherings of the court and take his turn composing in harmonious exchange?

    I have heard that the late Emperor possessed heaven-bestowed wisdom, and his compositions flowed like divine inspiration. Blessed with an era of great peace and prolonged civilization, he constantly gathered with men of letters and recluse-scholars such as Guo Yu, crafting poems and songs. Their rhythms rang like struck bells and vibrating jade, resonating with the melodies of Shao and Jun, spreading through the world until ten thousand mouths sang their praises. Truly a glorious achievement of a peaceful age! What is now called the Collection of Poetic Exchanges of Emperor Yejong is precisely this—circulated in the world for many years, though I had not yet had the honor to peruse it. Only recently, obtaining it at another's house, did I reverently read it through. Imagining before my eyes the noble gathering of sovereign and ministers of our age, my sighs proved insufficient, and I found tears streaming unbidden down my face.

    My only regret is that I was not born in that time, to stand among the court poets and strike the humble pipes, adding my voice to heaven's music. Yet now the present ruler loves literature even more dearly. Should lasting peace come about soon, might I too have such fortune? Why then lament a birth in another age?
  footnotes:
    - Shen Quan-qi, Song Zhi-wen, and the other poets mentioned were celebrated Tang Dynasty literary figures, representing the heights of poetic excellence.
    - The melodies Shao and Jun refer to legendary ancient Chinese musical compositions of supreme harmony.
    - The 'humble pipes' or cithara (缶) represents the author's modest role, in contrast to the imperial grandeur of participating in the emperor's verse exchange.
